features: 96 Keys, Redefine Full-Size Keyboards - Only 6 keys missing, the 96% keyboard with a number pad and offset arrow keys is built for productivity and a tactile typing experience.

BT5.0/2.4G/USB-C - Believe it or not, this is the first generation of three-mode wireless keyboards. Wireless mode with stable BT5.0, hassle-free 2.4Ghz dongle plus USB-C wired mode set no limits about your keyboard connection.
Hot-swappable - Hot-swap PCB allows you to replace 3 pins/5 pins switches freely without soldering issue. Enjoy the fun of making your own keyboard.
Ergonomic Magnetic Wrist Rest - To improve comfort over extended gaming sessions with built-in magnets for convenient attachment.
Hub Design - This wireless mechanical keyboard is armed with 2 built-in USB pass-through ports and 1 Type-C Port, allowing to back up more facilities, like a mouse or a headphone.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on August 20, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Great keyboard, but I just like full-sized keyboards
reviews.reviewText: The media could not be loaded. This was a great keyboard for the quality and price! I tried using the regular Keychron K4 with red switches, but I found the keys to be a bit mushy and too easy to press, causing typos. This keyboard from RK is much better; the yellow switches feel way more consistent but still smooth, and it is really appreciated that they have space between the numpad and enter key, which I constantly had problems with on the K4. The keyboard is light, but still feels solid which could make it good for travel. The volume wheel is also such a nice bonus! The only reason why I returned it was because I use the home, end, pg up, and pg down keys alot, so I decided to get a full-sized keyboard.If you are looking for a 96% keyboard however, you WILL NOT be disappointed!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 24, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Solid keyboard for the sale price
reviews.reviewText: I was on the fence on getting this keyboard, mainly because I like silent linear switches, but I saw the price and the capabilities of it and thought, "Ehhh why not try it out"... Gotta say I'm massivly impressed, I'm still not a fan of the type of switches but it is a very smooth, chuncky sound...IDK how to explain it but it sound delicious ;)I was looking for a possible replacement for my Corsair Strafe RGB mk.2 because sodering is a pain to replace the keys. This boards switches are slighty stiffer which I do like in comparason to the Cherry MX Reds, The reds caused constant miss-types due to the sensitive accuation, perfect for gaming but not typing.Overall I just wish this came with a Doubleshot keycap because it is difficult to see in a dark room. I'm happy with this in comparason to what I had and may have found that replacement I was looking for.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 23, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Clean Feel Sound and Style
reviews.reviewText: The style ,sound, feel, RGB & weight are all fantastic.If this is your size keyboard and you want something under 100$ this is as good as it gets. I have no testimony towards duribility of paint of battery life yet.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 7, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Amazing budget stock keyboard
reviews.reviewText: Note: I'm not a mechanical keyboard enthusiast. My review is based on my own personal experience.For starters, I really like the RK yellow switches that come with this keyboard. It has a nice tactile feel on all buttons and the sound that each keypress produces is satisfying to my ears. I am currently using this plugged in, but I have also tried the 2.4G wireless mode and it was also good. What I am really impressed by with this keyboard though is how compact it is for the 96 key form factor. After daily driving my DROP TKL keyboard for a few years, I was surprised to find that this is almost the same size as that keyboard. The switches are hot-swappable, so you can replace them with most of the 3 pin or 5 pin mechanical switches out there.As for some of the drawbacks, the wrist rest is not great and should either be replaced with a good quality one (like the GMK wooden wrist rest) or just not used entirely. The build quality of this keyboard is not as premium as my DROP keyboard, but that's a given considering the price and it doesn't feel like cheap plastic was used here.Overall, I'm actually quite pleased with this keyboard. I would recommend this as a great starter mechanical keyboard.
